## Observed Loss Behaviour (Typical for Protein Dataset)

| Epoch Range | Observation |
|-------------|-------------|
| 1 – 15 | Both losses drop sharply — model learns basic structure shapes |
| 15 – 40 | Steady decrease — learning helix vs sheet distinction |
| 40 – 55 | Val loss plateaus; train loss continues to decrease |
| 55+ | Val loss rises → **overfitting begins** |
| **Best epoch: ~50** | Minimum val loss, maximum generalisation |

> `best.pt` is automatically saved at the epoch with the lowest validation loss.
> This is the file to use for inference.

---

## Why Protein Structures Are Challenging to Detect

| Challenge | Impact |
|-----------|--------|
| Small objects (10–25% of frame) | Harder to localise precisely |
| High visual similarity between classes | Helix and sheet ribbons look similar at low resolution |
| Multiple objects per frame | Requires good NMS tuning |
| Dynamic appearance (frame-to-frame vibration) | Augmentation critical |
| Class imbalance (more helices than sheets in most proteins) | Monitor per-class precision |

**Mitigations applied:**
- `degrees=15` rotation augmentation handles trajectory viewpoint variation
- `mosaic=1.0` creates varied training contexts
- `patience=20` prevents over-training
- Per-class evaluation in confusion matrix tracks class imbalance effects

